{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516715"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:45:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:45:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12706"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12706"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.45,0.04,0.01,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5162"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50589"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5162"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12706"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35808"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2078"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8719"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8902"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42800"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50589"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman presents to the Emergency department of an urban hospital with a four-hour history of left-sided chest pain with onset at rest. There is no nausea or vomiting, no radiation of the pain, and no associated sweating. She has had similar but more transient episodes of chest pain previously, which would improve with sublingual nitroglycerin. Her medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and a 30-pack-year smoking history. Her regular medications include aspirin, metformin, lisinopril, atorvastatin, and she takes sublingual nitroglycerin as needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer blood pressure is 136/76 mmHg, pulse 105/min, temperature 36.1 \u00b0C, and respiratory rate 20/min. Her lungs are clear on auscultation, her heart sounds are dual, there is no JVP elevation, and no peripheral oedema. An ECG shows ST depression in lateral leads. The serum troponin is 0.50 ng/mL (\u0026lt; 0.04).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has already been given aspirin 300\u00a0mg in the ambulance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important immediate medical intervention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alteplase","Heparin","Hydralazine","Furosemide","Digoxin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most probable diagnosis in this patient is an acute coronary syndrome, specifically an NSTEMI. Acute coronary syndrome refers to a group of conditions that include ST-elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI), non-ST elevation myocardial infarction (NSTEMI) and unstable angina. It is usually a result of plaque disruption in coronary arteries (atherosclerosis). Common risk factors for this disease include smoking, hypertension, diabetes, hyperlipidaemia, male sex, physical inactivity, family obesity and poor nutritional practices.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeparin\u003C/strong\u003E is an anticoagulant that is used to prevent further clot formation and reduce the risk of complications in patients with acute coronary syndromes. Heparin forms part of the standard treatment for NSTEMI and has been shown to decrease mortality. Unless there are any contraindications, unfractionated or low-molecular weight heparin can be used. Dual antiplatelet therapy with ticagrelor or clopidogrel may also be recommended, especially when percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) is planned.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlteplase\u003C/strong\u003E is a thrombolytic agent that is used to dissolve blood clots in patients with acute STEMI who do not have immediate access to PCI. This patient\u0027s ECG does not show ST elevation, so it is not indicated in this case. Thrombolysis is not indicated in the majority of NSTEMI cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydralazine\u003C/strong\u003E is a vasodilator that is used to treat hypertension and congestive heart failure. It is not indicated in this case as the patient\u0027s blood pressure is not markedly elevated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E is a loop diuretic that is used to treat fluid overload in patients with congestive heart failure. It is not indicated in this case as the patient does not have any evidence of fluid overload on physical examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigoxin\u003C/strong\u003E is a cardiac glycoside that is used to treat heart failure and atrial fibrillation. It is not indicated in this case, as the patient does not have evidence of atrial fibrillation on ECG, and she does not have any evidence of congestive heart failure on physical examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntiplatelet therapy is recommended in patients with an NSTEMI. This patient is already on aspirin and so would not require additional aspirin in the emergent setting. The choice and timing of a second anti-platelet will depend upon the timing of angiography as well as cardiology advice. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAngiography is an important consideration in suspected acute coronary syndromes, especially where there are persistent symptoms, elevated cardiac biomarkers, or ST-segment changes on electrocardiogram. Angiography can help to identify the location and severity of blockages in the coronary arteries, and may be followed by PCI which is a minimally invasive procedure that can be used to treat coronary artery blockages.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor patients recovering post acute management of ACS, it is essential to address cardiac risk factors in order to reduce their risk of future cardiovascular events. This includes smoking cessation, lipid management with an LDL target of 1.4 mmol/L, blood pressure control to a target of \u0026lt;140/90, glycaemic control and weight management. A heart-healthy lifestyle with regular exercise and a balanced diet should also be encouraged, and regular follow-up appointments should be scheduled to monitor progress, adjust medications as needed, and provide ongoing support regarding cardiac risk factor management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Heparin is a recommended initial treatment for NSTEMI and has been shown to decrease mortality"],"references":["Singh A, Museedi AS, Grossman SA. Acute Coronary Syndrome. [Updated 2022 Jul 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-.","National Heart Foundation of Australia and Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand. (2016). Australian Clinical Guidelines for the Management of Acute Coronary Syndromes 2016."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35808"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12706"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35808"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-14T09:18:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-14T09:19:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5162"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50589"}}},"me